:::summary
The Vikings were Norse seafarers from Scandinavia who, between roughly 793 and 1100 AD, raided, traded, explored, and settled across an extraordinary range of the world — from Newfoundland in the west to the Volga River in the east. Fierce warriors and skilled navigators, they also produced a rich literary and mythological tradition and left their mark on the cultures of Britain, France, Russia, and the North Atlantic.
:::

